<div class="container fade-in">

  <!-- What is Bcrypt -->
  <div class="section">
    <div class="section__header">
      <div class="section__number">Section 6.1</div>
      <h2 class="section__title">What is Bcrypt?</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="section__content">
      <p><strong>Bcrypt</strong> is a password hashing function designed by Niels Provos and David Mazières in 1999, based on the Blowfish cipher. It's specifically designed for password storage — it's intentionally <strong>slow</strong> (unlike MD5/SHA which are designed to be fast), making brute-force attacks computationally expensive.</p>
      <p>The key innovation of bcrypt is its <strong>adaptive cost factor</strong>: as hardware gets faster, you can increase the cost factor to keep the hash computation equally expensive to brute-force.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="info-box info-box--explain">
      <div class="info-box__title">ℹ️ Why Not MD5/SHA for Passwords?</div>
      <div class="info-box__content">
        <div class="table-wrap" style="margin:12px 0;">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Algorithm</th><th>Hashes/sec (GPU)</th><th>Time to crack 8-char password</th><th>Suitable for passwords?</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td><code>MD5</code></td><td>~25 billion/sec</td><td>~2 minutes</td><td>❌ Way too fast</td></tr>
              <tr><td><code>SHA-256</code></td><td>~8 billion/sec</td><td>~7 minutes</td><td>❌ Still too fast</td></tr>
              <tr><td><code>Bcrypt (cost 12)</code></td><td>~25,000/sec</td><td>~12 years</td><td>✅ Purpose-built</td></tr>
              <tr><td><code>Argon2id</code></td><td>~5,000/sec</td><td>~60 years</td><td>✅ Gold standard</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
        <p>Fast hash functions (MD5, SHA) are designed for data integrity checks, not password storage. A GPU can compute billions of MD5 hashes per second, making brute force trivial.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

